SIMPLE: loath
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Loath
<hw>Loath</hw> <pr>(l⟦omac⟧th)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>looth</ets>, <ets>loth</ets>, AS. <ets>l⟦amac⟧⟦edh⟧</ets> hostile,
odious; akin to OS. <ets>l⟦amac⟧⟦edh⟧</ets>, G. <ets>leid</ets>, Icel.
<ets>lei⟦edh⟧r</ets>, Sw. <ets>led</ets>, G. <ets>leiden</ets> to
suffer, OHG. <ets>l⟦imac⟧dan</ets> to suffer, go, cf. AS.
<ets>l⟦imac⟧⟦edh⟧an</ets> to go, Goth. <ets>leipan</ets>, and E.
<ets>lead</ets> to guide.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Hateful; odious;
disliked.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Filled with disgust or aversion; averse; unwilling;
reluctant; <as>as, <ex>loath</ex> to part</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Full <qex>loth</qex> were him to curse for his tithes.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Why, then, though <qex>loath</qex>, yet must I be content.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Loathe</ent>⟦br⟧
